    <text type="letter">
        <body>
            <pb xml:id="leaf001r" facs="loc.02050.001_large.jpg" type="recto"/>
            <note type="editorial" resp="#ht" place="top">see notes Aug 26 &amp; 30, '88</note>
            <opener>
                <dateline>
                    <name type="place"><handShift rend="printed"/>THE SATURDAY UNION. <lb/>A Literary and Political Newspaper. <lb/>LARGEST CIRCULATION OF THE LYNN WEEKLIES. <lb/>SMYTHE &amp; FOSS, Publishers. <lb/>Lynn, Mass.</name>
                    <date when="1884-05-26"><handShift rend="manuscript"/>May 26 1884</date>
                </dateline>
                <salute>Mr. Walt Whitman:</salute>
                <salute>Dear Sir,</salute>
            </opener>
            <p>I send you with this letter two copies of our paper, both
                containing notices of your poems. Permit me to thank you warmly for the great
                inspiration I have received from the reading of <hi rend="underline">Leaves of Grass</hi>. In my opinion, it marks a new era in American
                Literature; and is to stand out more and more prominently, as time advances, as the
                distinctively American book </p>
            <closer>
                <salute>Most Respectfully,</salute>
                <signed>S. W. Foss</signed>
            </closer>
            
            <pb xml:id="leaf001v" facs="loc.02050.002_large.jpg" type="verso"/>
            <note type="editorial" resp="#unk" place="right">SW Foss</note>
        </body>
